cs.SI, cs.CR, cs.SD, cs.HC, cs.CY 

This paper deals with the problem of detecting Sybils (fake accounts) in online social networks (OSNs) using a crowdsourcing approach. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), which deals with the study of social networks and their properties. The paper also discusses the security implications of Sybils, which makes cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) another likely category. The paper also involves a user study to evaluate the effectiveness of the proposed approach, which falls under the category of cs.SD (Software Engineering). Additionally, the paper discusses the role of human experts and turkers in the crowdsourcing approach, which falls under the category of cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Finally, the paper discusses the scalability of the proposed approach, which falls under the category of cs.CY (Computers and Society).
